Date: Fri 28 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source; Xinhuanet News Agency, Fri 28 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-01/28/content_2518704.htm>

Viet Nam: 3 More Avian Influenza Cases Reported
-------------------------------------------------
Viet Nam has just found 3 more people in the country's northern region to
have contracted avian influenza A (H5N1) virus infection, raising the total
in the country to 16 since late December 2004.
Initial tests by the National Hygiene and Epidemiology Institute show that
samples from a 66-year-old from Hanoi city, a 30-year-old from Hung Yen
province, and a 30-year-old from Phu Tho province were positive for the
virus, the local newspaper Labor reported on Fri 28 Jan 2005.
The patients, who are receiving treatment at the Hanoi-based Tropical
Disease Institute, are all in stable condition. The 30-year-olds, who were
hospitalized on 22 Jan 2005 and 23 Jan 2005, respectively, had contact with
sick fowl. The reason for [infection] of the 66-year-old, who was admitted
to hospital on 25 Jan 2005, is under investigation.
2 local people, a 15-year-old teenager from southern Kien Giang province
and a 24-year-old woman from central Binh Dinh province, have just been
admitted to provincial hospitals after showing symptoms of high
temperature, cough, and damaged lungs. The patients are suspected to have
contracted H5N1, since they either ate chicken or traded poultry.
Among the 16 cases of avian influenza infection nationwide, 9, including 8
from the southern region and one from the northern region, have died.
However, the Ministry of Health has so far confirmed [only] 10 out of the
16 cases. The 1st case in the northern region, a 42-year-old man in Hanoi,
is set to be discharged from the Tropical Disease Institute on Fri 28 Jan 2005.
Avian influenza has stricken 27 cities and provinces nationwide, killing
and leading to the forced culling of more than 812 000 fowl, according to
the Department of Animal Health.
